No place to stay

Judith, 26, Daigou

I went to Europe on the 15th, after the 25th return to China, Wuhan Airport has been closed, we are in place at the airport scattered. I took the train for more than 10 hours and arrived at Jiujiang, Jiangxi Province at 4:30 am on the 26th. I wanted to stay overnight and then cross the Yangtze River Bridge back to Wuhan.

I had no idea that for the next seven or eight hours, a series of rejections would await me.

I first called the seven-day hotel chain in Jiujiang and was told it was a tourist from Wuhan who turned me down. Hanting also refused. I went to another local hotel and said it was no problem. When I got there in my car, the girl at the front desk told me that the manager wouldn't let me stay here. I couldn't get out of town, I couldn't get into the store, so I called 110 for help. In the meantime, I called the CDC to report my trip. They said yes, and nothing more.

20 minutes later, the police came, said can not make a decision, please come to see my local neighborhood. Two hours later, the neighborhood committee came, when I have not had a good rest for more than ten hours, jet lag is not completely good, sleepy and tired. They took my temperature, 37.1 degrees. Seeing this number, the two policemen first told me to leave, after the report did not allow me to leave, took me to the hospital.

At the hospital, I paid for all the tests myself, and the tests came back normal, but I still couldn't go anywhere. I Want my dad to drive to the other side of the Yangtze River Bridge to pick me up and ask the police to take me to the Yangtze River Bridge. But the Yangtze River Bridge is also closed to pedestrians.

CHEST CT results

Later, the police sent me to the rescue center, the door posted a notice, write the host: Minors, beggars, homeless homeless homeless... The more I think the more bitter.

As soon as enters the door, the person inside also talks like quarrels, does not have the temperature through the mask: "You are from Wuhan, now which does not fear Wuhan's. ". It was raining outside, and I sat down on the stool with a bag on my back and two suitcases on my back, hoping he would speak softly to me.

There is an iron sliding door outside the shelter, and inside are several rooms, four beds each, no suitcases allowed, and even carry on bags left outside. They told me that the Three Meals a Day had an aunt who gave them away for free. I lost my temper when they asked me to check in with my handprint, tears streaming down my face. Well, I've been to a dozen countries, and it's not like I can't afford a hotel, and now I'm homeless and institutionalized.

I stayed at the rescue center until after 11:00, kept trying to get in touch with the hotel, and finally found another hotel that would let me stay. After getting into the taxi, the driver heard that I was from Wuhan. He braked suddenly, jumped out of the driver's seat and ran to the rescue center? "

In the rescue center's guarantee, he finally pulled me out, all the way to blame Wuhan people eating game, said the people of the country for you to become so. I didn't have the strength to argue with him. I just wanted to get to the hotel quickly.

At the new hotel, the early morning thing happened again, and I was not allowed to stay, but I could not walk any more. I told them that I had called the police and had been to the hospital for an examination, but the hotel staff insisted on taking me to the neighborhood committee to take my temperature, so we went, according to the Neighborhood Association, there's no thermometer.

It was already one o'clock in the afternoon. Seeing that I couldn't bear it any longer, the hotel checked me in. So, after 30 hours without sleep or food, I finally found a hotel to take me in.

Yesterday, a friend drove to pick me up, took a very tortuous route, I finally went home, no one to chase me.

Disclosure of personal information

###Wu Qing, 23, medical student

On December 31,2019, when I saw a screenshot of Dr. Li Wenliang on Wechat and a CT scan of a pneumonia patient, I paid attention to wearing a mask. But at the time, Li Wenliang was criticized, and for a long time, I didn't hear about pneumonia. It wasn't until January 19th, when everyone was talking, about which hospital had a lot of patients with high fever and staff infection, that I panicked, and that day I had a CT at the hospital and there was nothing wrong with it.

On January 21, I took the high-speed train back to my hometown in Shandong Province. On the train, I wore a mask the whole time. About going home, actually quite tangled, afraid to bring pneumonia to the family. When I was attacked for suggesting not to visit in the New Year, my parents said I was exaggerating, bluffing, lying and spreading rumors.

Home that two days, I heard some doctors have been infected, on the 23rd, went to the county hospital for a physical examination. The doctor at the county hospital heard that I came back from Wuhan, took my temperature, it was 37.2, so they put me in isolation, I am also a medical student, I know 37.2 is not a fever in medicine, only 37.3 degrees, and I have a little hyperthyroidism, the basal body temperature is relatively high. I explained it to him, but he still wrote "fever" on my chart and said I had double-breasted, but he didn't listen to me, and my C.T. and blood work were normal.

But I went home and isolated myself. To my Surprise, later, my personal information was leaked. It started out as a Excel  form with information about hundreds of people, the train they were taking back from Wuhan, their ID numbers and addresses, including some names and phone numbers.

I didn't pay much attention to it at the time, but then a lot of people added me to Wechat and said they wanted me to be safe. I was very surprised. I passed a few of them and wanted to ask about the situation. They sent me a screenshot of the statistics of some fever patients'information in our county, my Name, ID number, address, temperature, and telephone number were written in it.

I reached out to a few of the people on the screenshot, who are also in quarantine at home, and are trying to work out the privacy issues, and no one is making any progress.

I am still in self-isolation period, do not know when to go back to Wuhan, how to go back, but I really want to go back to Wuhan, even if it is to the hospital on duty, or in the dormitory alone.

I was very unhappy in my hometown, my information was leaked, I wanted to solve this problem, but everyone told you, don't make trouble, these days I feel very upset, when I first came back, I always felt guilty, to my family and every department, but right now, I feel like I'm being sacrificed.

Refused to board

Shi Li, 40, office worker

We are from Wuhan to Japan on the afternoon of the 20th, originally planned to return to Wuhan on the 27th. The itinerary was set in early December 2019, and the package tour is non-refundable, nearly 30,000 yuan.

Before we left, news reports of pneumonia in Wuhan were not that serious, saying that only limited human to human transmission, we took the subway to see many people do not wear masks. On the afternoon of the 20th, we went to the airport to take infrared temperature and left the country smoothly. It was only a few days after arriving in Japan that the outbreak was known. If we'd known it was gonna be this hard to get home, we never would have gotten out.

On the 24th, we learned that our return flight had been canceled. There was chaos both at home and abroad. We had to buy our own tickets and return to other cities in the country to try again. Our Group of 28, including my family, had nine people on the flight from Nagoya to Shanghai and then to Changsha. At the gate we learned that there were 19 people on the same flight from Wuhan, and we didn't know each other.

Half an hour before boarding, there was a problem. More than 60 non-wuhan passengers held up the airport ground crew and said they would not agree to fly with us. These days, we are very low-key outside, for fear of being known, especially the Chinese, we are Wuhan people, because you can not predict what will encounter. But they knew that some of them spoke Japanese, had been talking to the crew, and were reluctant to get on the same plane as us.

Then we got on the plane, and the crew took our temperature again and again to make sure we didn't have a fever, and the electronic thermometers, the mercury thermometers, went back and forth, talking to people who didn't want to get on the plane. We were stuck in the cabin for five hours, until we got some people on board, sitting in the forward cabin, far away from us. Some of the luggage was unloaded, and some people didn't take it. From 9:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. local time, our plane took off and arrived in Shanghai just after 4:00 p.m.

Image source network for body temperature monitoring

When we were in Japan, our guide told us that we could extend our visas for 30 days for a 4,000 yen fee, but we never wanted to stay in Japan. In fact, if we did get pneumonia, we'd have someone in Japan to take care of it, free of charge, and better medical resources. But we want to go home, there are four old people in our home in Wuhan, they can not drive without us, every day all the time in the message, told them not to go out, afraid they did not eat and drink.

When we were in Japan, we wore masks whenever we were outside. From Nagoya to Mount Fuji, Tokyo, Ōsaka and Nara, Japanese guides accompanied us through the eight days, and finally took us to the airport and watched US leave through security. We were also very cooperative and did not want to cause any trouble. On the plane, our seats were all arranged behind 60 rows. There were three people from Wuhan who sat in 45 rows, but later they were also very conscious of sitting in 60 rows.

In fact, when I bought this ticket, I thought the worst case scenario, after returning home may be unified resettlement, isolation, these we are ready, this is an irresistible force, but at least we are closer to home. If you look at our overseas group, more than 95% of people want to go home by any means. But at the airport, when we saw the people who refused to board the plane, we were so scared that we wouldn't be able to go back this time. I just thought I'd come back, even if you drove us all the way back to Hubei.

After getting off the plane at 4 p.m. in Shanghai, the epidemic prevention personnel repeatedly checked our body temperature. After 8 p.m. , we were uniformly sent to the hotel and later taken to an infectious disease hospital in Pudong for a virus test. We found out through a press conference in Shanghai that the test results were all negative, but to be sure, we are still in isolation in the hospital, waiting for a second test.

We were willing to do the tests, we were willing to be quarantined, but the thought of that morning when the Chinese refused to board the same flight made us feel very sick. We can even understand their rejection of us, but we are also victims of this epidemic and can not go home.

On This Day, all hotels do not accept Hubei tourists. The unified statement of the boss is, the government policy is this, Hubei can not do live. They're wearing masks. They're telling us to leave. Don't let it interfere with their business.

I called the Jinghong Public Security Bureau in Xishuangbanna. At 12 o'clock, the police from the Public Security Bureau came and gave us a statement. I've been going over my route in detail, and everyone I've spoken to has, but when it's done, they said it was just for the call and the notes.

I had to keep calling, the mayor's hotline told me to call the tourist board, the Tourist Board told me to call the city's CDC, and the number sent by the staff was either an empty number or a wrong number... after making numerous calls, the CDC finally offered me a few hotels to go to. These hotels, either full, or let us go to the hospital to open a certificate, finally found a hotel, standard room price 680 yuan a night, far higher than the normal price, this time is 11 pm, I feel very tired. The next day, the hotel had to renew, but I didn't want to get ripped off again. I called the CDC again. I called the tourist board. On January 19, after studying in Shenzhen, I went to Shanghai because two days later I was taking my mother and child on a cruise to Fukuoka.

At the request of the tour guide, we took our temperature repeatedly, ate once, washed our hands once, and then took the temperature again when the hotel came out. I used to travel and wish I could take a photo five times a day, but I wasn't in the mood to take a photo on the first day in Japan.

Back home that day is the 25th, Wuhan has been closed, the home of all the train shows sold out. Our heart is very cool, hurriedly buy a mask, want to block the germs also want to block said Wuhan People's gossip. Walk home

Cui Tao, 20, auto dealer

When we left Wuhan Tianhe Airport for Sanya on January 22, we also wore masks on the plane we went to, thinking it would be OK. At that time, we did not know that the pneumonia epidemic was so serious. On the 23rd, the city of Wuhan was closed, we wanted to go home, but we couldn't, and Sanya was closed.

We were in Haikou on the 25th. The hotel has stopped providing hot water for our room. When I called the citizens'help line that day, I got a 12345: No island, you can go, but if you can go back to your place, I don't know, you have to contact the local authorities. After hanging up, we decided to go home.

I called a friend of Qianjiang's, and he said, the highway's open, he can come back. The idea was to find a way to get to Yueyang, take a bus to Qianjiang, and have a friend pick us up on the other side.

We arrived in Yueyang at 10:30 pm on the 25th, and it took more than an hour and more than 20 hotels to find a hotel that would accept us. Then a friend in Qianjiang called and said the highway was closed, no one could get in or out. I felt helpless, but I just kept going.

After a night in Yueyang, the next day, we got a taxi to cross the bridge to Qianjiang. It took us a long time to persuade the driver to take us. He finally agreed, but he didn't want to cross the bridge. We had to get out and walk across.

It was a little after 11 a.m. on January 26, and the three of US started from the Jingyue Bridge in Yueyang and crossed it on foot. The tollbooth guy asks where we're going, we say Jingzhou, Jianli County, and he tells us to pull over and be safe.

About 10 minutes later, a traffic cop showed up, figured someone saw us on the highway and called it in. The traffic policeman followed us all the way, told us to pull over, to be careful, helped us put our luggage in the trunk of the police car, and accompanied us all the way to the other side of the bridge, although he didn't let us get in the car, but we understood, they can help us put our stuff in the car. We're already warm.

It was a cloudy day. The wind was strong on the bridge and the Yangtze River was below. We walked for two hours and more than 10 kilometers. On the way, we saw a boy and a girl walking on the bridge. They were all alone.

After getting off the bridge, our friend drove US home after a long detour. For most of our lives, nothing happens, and everyone looks the same, but in this case, all kinds of humanity show up. I would like to emphasize that we Hubei people do not want to run around, we did not mean to come out, after coming out, everywhere do not like us, again and again drive, we have to leave.

Walking on the bridge, very tired, but the heart is stable, because you know you are going home. I'm happy to be back in Qianjiang, happier than I was when I left, and although there are fewer people on the streets and everyone is wearing masks, you'll feel safe.

Cyberbullying

Wu Yan, 40, innkeeper

I am from Wuhan. I have run a bed-and-breakfast in Dali for six years. Starting January 25, the hotel in Dali began to refuse entry to people from Wuhan. I posted information on the Internet to accommodate people from Wuhan who had nowhere to go, but I was unexpectedly confronted with unprecedented cyber violence.

The ugly insults haven't stopped since that day. Some people call me a "dirty clown, " "ugly Mutt, " which is a polite term, and some people just curse, "your family is going to die tonight. ".

They called my mother names. They called my family names. UNBEKNOWNST to them, I come from a long line of doctors, many of whom work in Wuhan's health care system. I don't want to tell these relatives that their city and their families are going through this kind of humiliation because they want to help the people of Wuhan while they are fighting on the front lines.

I know more about disease prevention and disinfection than most people who swear at me. My bed-and-breakfast is filled with boxes of disinfectant. Before and after the reception, I carefully disinfected myself. This has been my daily routine since I opened the bed-and-breakfast.

When I heard the news that Wuhan people had nowhere to go, I decided without hesitation to provide them with accommodation. My mother also firmly supported me. Moreover, I said that people from Wuhan who came to my hostel could enjoy a preferential price of 100 yuan a night.

More than a dozen Wuhan townsfolk rushed over one after another. Elsewhere, they've been rejected a million times. Unfortunately, I only have ten rooms, and I have other guests, so I can only handle so many people. The Wuhan guests stayed only two nights and went to a hotel in Dali.

But even after they left, the violence and the hurt didn't go away. The name-calling hasn't stopped, and a lot of people have reported me anonymously.

On the 27th, the police came to my hostel twice. They looked at my health report and identity information, and registered all the information of the tourists who stayed in Wuhan. Near my shop, a private car with Hubei license plates was also smashed. Two people were sitting in the car. A group of villagers wearing face masks surrounded the car. The front glass of the car was smashed into a hole, like a spider's Web. Others thought it was my car, and commented on the Internet, "that boss got his car vandalized. Bad Karma. ". "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The window that was smashed into a spider's Web

On the 28th, a villager led the secretary of our village to a bed-and-breakfast and warned me, "if you dare to receive guests from Wuhan Again, we will revoke your business license and drive you out of the village. ". "I can only say rest assured, I will not receive any more visitors.

Now, the mobile phone or continue to send strange text messages, insult me. I had to turn the sound off. A man who used to sleep with his eyes closed till dawn now wakes up with a start, thinking the police are going to knock on my door, like it's some kind of crime.

I think the only people involved were some of my regulars, who had to be quarantined with us for 14 days.

This week, I was scolded some out of control, can only rely on singing vent every day, a week recorded more than 30 songs. On the evening of the 28th, the Fourth Day of my encounter with cyber-violence, I began to delete those insults and comments one by one. I deleted more than 20 minutes, leaving more than 10 pages to be deleted.

After this time, the thing I am most worried about is the psychological trauma of the Wuhan People. Of course we understand your fears, but why can't we be nice to our fellow man? I love the sunshine in Dali, but after this disaster, I want to go back to Wuhan.

Be kind to

Old O, 49, real estate manager

If we knew the Wuhan epidemic was so serious, then our family wouldn't have gone anywhere.

But on the road, there are a lot of people took out their cell phones to shoot us, look at our eyes, like the God of plague.

The burnt license plate

We spent the Spring Festival in self-isolation. By the 27th, we couldn't find any hotel in Hainan to take us in, the designated hotel in Haikou was either full or out of business, and we had nowhere to go.

I looked it up on the Internet, and when I saw that Zhanjiang was taking Wuhan people in, I decided to take a boat to Guangdong.

When we got off the boat, we called the mayor of Zhanjiang hotline, and they immediately pointed us to a hotel in Xuwen. It was one o'clock in the night and there were volunteers waiting at the door.

After taking our temperature and checking in, we finally found a place to stop. The two buildings here are fully occupied, more than 100 people from Wuhan live here.

Here, we finally feel a little warmth. Every morning, medical staff would come to take our temperature. We normally wore masks to protect ourselves. No one made the dreaded gesture of handing the thermometer to us from afar.

Food and lodging are all free here. Three Meals a Day is a nutritious mix of steamed chicken and green vegetables at noon and local specialties at night. In case we didn't have enough to eat, the volunteers also bought US instant noodles, yogurt, juice, mineral water and beer, and provided us with apples, oranges, oranges and winter dates every day. On top of a piece of Durian cake given to us, there was a small yellow note that read, "Brothers share weal and woe. ". "

These days, more than 100 people in Wuhan have normal body temperature. We set up a group. If we need something, we write it down in the group, and then the volunteers help us buy it. In Xuwen, masks are not available, but local volunteers are sending them to us these days, making it a priority to ensure the supply of Wuhan people in the hotel. The volunteers also said that if they were not satisfied with the conditions, they could change to another hotel.

We are very grateful for what we have been through in Zhanjiang. I had SARS in 2003, and I remember what it was like. That year, many people from Guangdong and Beijing ran to our Wuhan, see the license plates of the two cars, we are sympathetic, welcome, never reported. The hotel is open and I made a donation for the SARS outbreak.

I believe that no matter which city the epidemic occurs in, the reason is as the volunteers gave us another small note that said: "Your City is sick, but will soon be cured, we all people together Cheer Ha. ". "

At the request of the interviewee, all the characters in the article are assumed names
